      "raw_response": "{\n  \"final_bugs\": [\n    {\n      \"description\": \"The dynamic programming implementation has cubic time complexity (O(k * n^2)), which is far too slow for the given constraints (n up to 2000, sum of n over all test cases \u2264 2000). This will cause the program to exceed the time limit on larger test cases.\",\n      \"triggering_input\": \"1\\n2000 2000\\n\" + \" \".join([\"1\"] * 2000) + \"\\n\",\n      \"fix\": \"Replace the DP with a greedy/linear solution: compute d_i = i - a_i for all i where a_i \u2264 i, sort the d_i values, and find the smallest x such that at least k of them satisfy d_i \u2264 x. The answer is that minimal x, or -1 if fewer than k such elements exist. This runs in O(n log n) time.\",\n      \"confirmed\": true,\n      \"reasoning\": \"The original DP loops over cnt (up to k), j (up to n), and i (up to j), resulting in ~4\u202f\u00d7\u202f10\u2079 iterations for the worst case, which cannot finish within typical time limits. The greedy approach is the standard solution for this problem and meets the required complexity.\"\n    }\n  ]\n}",
